    "levelBg": "#DCFCE7",
    "levelText": "#16A34A",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "title": "Grundkonzept · Basic Concept",
        "text": "The present tense (Präsens) is formed by removing the -en ending from the infinitive and adding personal endings. It's used for current, habitual, and even future events.",
        "bullets": [
          "Remove -en from the infinitive to get the stem",
          "Add endings: -e, -st, -t, -en, -t, -en",
          "Some verbs have stem changes (e→i, a→ä)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "conjugation",
        "title": "Regelmäßige Konjugation: lernen",
        "color": "amber",
        "rows": [
          {
            "left": "ich",
            "right": "lern-e"
          },
          {
            "left": "du",
            "right": "lern-st"
          },
          {
            "left": "er/sie/es",
            "right": "lern-t"
          },
          {
            "left": "wir",
            "right": "lern-en"
          },
          {
            "left": "ihr",
            "right": "lern-t"
          },
          {
            "left": "Sie/sie",
            "right": "lern-en"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "conjugation",
        "title": "Unregelmäßig: sein & haben",
        "color": "orange",
        "rows": [
          {
            "left": "ich",
            "right": "bin / habe"
          },
          {
            "left": "du",
            "right": "bist / hast"
          },
          {
            "left": "er/sie/es",
            "right": "ist / hat"
          },
          {
            "left": "wir",
            "right": "sind / haben"
          },
          {
            "left": "ihr",
            "right": "seid / habt"
          },
          {
            "left": "Sie/sie",
            "right": "sind / haben"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "tip",
        "text": "Verbs with stems ending in -t, -d add an extra 'e' before -st and -t: du arbeit-e-st, er arbeit-e-t.",
        "variant": "warning"
      },
      {
        "type": "examples",
        "title": "Beispiele",
        "color": "amber",
        "items": [
          {
            "de": "Ich lerne Deutsch.",
            "en": "I am learning German."
          },
          {
            "de": "Du arbeitest jeden Tag.",
            "en": "You work every day."
          },
          {
            "de": "Er spricht Englisch.",
            "en": "He speaks English. (e→i change)"
          },
          {
            "de": "Wir gehen morgen ins Kino.",
            "en": "We're going to the cinema tomorrow."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "comparison",
        "title": "Stammvokaländerungen",
        "headers": [
          "Typ",
          "Infinitiv",
          "er/sie/es"
        ],
        "rows": [
          ["e → i", "sprechen", "spricht"],
          ["e → i", "geben", "gibt"],
          ["e → i", "nehmen", "nimmt"],
          ["e → i", "essen", "isst"],
          ["e → i", "helfen", "hilft"],
          ["e → ie", "lesen", "liest"],
          ["e → ie", "sehen", "sieht"],
          ["e → ie", "empfehlen", "empfiehlt"],
          ["a → ä", "fahren", "fährt"],
          ["a → ä", "schlafen", "schläft"],
          ["a → ä", "tragen", "trägt"],
          ["au → äu", "laufen", "läuft"]
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "rules",
        "title": "Wichtige Regeln",
        "items": [
          "The verb always takes Position 2 in a statement.",
          "Stem-vowel changes only happen with du, er/sie/es.",
          "sein, haben, werden are fully irregular — memorize them.",
          "Präsens can express future if a time word is present: Morgen fahre ich."
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  "g9": {
    "id": "g9",
    "subtitle": "Satzbau · Grundstruktur",
    "emoji": "🏗️",
    "gradient": [
      "#06B6D4",
      "#3B82F6"
    ],
    "levelBg": "#DCFCE7",
    "levelText": "#16A34A",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "title": "Wortstellung · Word Order",
        "text": "In German, the conjugated verb ALWAYS stands in Position 2 in a main clause (Hauptsatz). The subject can move, but the verb stays put.",
        "bullets": [
          "Position 1: Subject or other element (time, place)",
          "Position 2: Conjugated verb (ALWAYS!)",
          "Position 3+: Other elements",
          "End: Second part of verb (participle, infinitive, prefix)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "transform",
        "title": "Verb in Position 2",
        "from": {
          "label": "NORMAL",
          "text": "Ich lerne heute Deutsch."
        },
        "to": {
          "label": "INVERSION",
          "text": "Heute lerne ich Deutsch."
        },
        "note": "When another element takes Position 1, subject moves after the verb"
      },
      {
        "type": "examples",
        "title": "Aussagesätze (Statements)",
        "color": "cyan",
        "items": [
          {
            "de": "Ich gehe morgen ins Kino.",
            "en": "I'm going to the cinema tomorrow."
          },
          {
            "de": "Morgen gehe ich ins Kino.",
            "en": "Tomorrow I'm going to the cinema."
          },
          {
            "de": "Im Kino sehe ich einen Film.",
            "en": "In the cinema I watch a film."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "examples",
        "title": "Ja/Nein-Fragen (Verb first!)",
        "color": "blue",
        "items": [
          {
            "de": "Lernst du Deutsch?",
            "en": "Are you learning German?"
          },
          {
            "de": "Gehst du morgen ins Kino?",
            "en": "Are you going to the cinema tomorrow?"
          },
          {
            "de": "Ist das dein Buch?",
            "en": "Is that your book?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "examples",
        "title": "W-Fragen",
        "color": "indigo",
        "items": [
          {
            "de": "Wer ist das?",
            "en": "Who is that?"
          },
          {
            "de": "Was machst du?",
            "en": "What are you doing?"
          },
          {
            "de": "Warum lernst du Deutsch?",
            "en": "Why are you learning German?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "rules",
        "title": "Merke dir!",
        "items": [
          "Verb ALWAYS in Position 2 in main clauses.",
          "Yes/No questions → verb in Position 1.",
          "W-questions → W-word in Position 1, verb in Position 2.",
          "und, oder, aber, denn don't change word order."
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  "g10": {
    "id": "g10",
    "subtitle": "Kasus · Fälle",
    "emoji": "🎯",
    "gradient": [
      "#8B5CF6",
      "#A855F7"
    ],
    "levelBg": "#DCFCE7",
    "levelText": "#16A34A",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "title": "Die vier Fälle · The Four Cases",
        "text": "German has four cases that change the form of articles, pronouns, and adjectives. Focus on Nominativ (subject) and Akkusativ (direct object) first.",
        "bullets": [
          "Nominativ = WER? (who?) → the subject",
          "Akkusativ = WEN? (whom?) → the direct object",
          "Dativ = WEM? (to whom?) → the indirect object",
          "Genitiv = WESSEN? (whose?) → possession"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "comparison",
        "title": "Artikel in Nominativ & Akkusativ",
        "headers": [
          "",
          "Nominativ",
          "Akkusativ"
        ],
        "rows": [
          [
            "Maskulin",
            "der / ein",
            "den / einen"
          ],
          [
            "Feminin",
            "die / eine",
            "die / eine"
          ],
          [
            "Neutrum",
            "das / ein",
            "das / ein"
          ],
          [
            "Plural",
            "die / –",
            "die / –"
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "tip",
        "text": "Only MASCULINE changes in the Akkusativ! der → den, ein → einen. Everything else stays the same.",
        "variant": "success"
      },
      {
        "type": "examples",
        "title": "Nominativ (Subjekt)",
        "color": "violet",
        "items": [
          {
            "de": "Der Mann liest.",
            "en": "The man reads. (WER liest?)"
          },
          {
            "de": "Die Frau kocht.",
            "en": "The woman cooks. (WER kocht?)"
          },
          {
            "de": "Das Kind spielt.",
            "en": "The child plays. (WER spielt?)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "examples",
        "title": "Akkusativ (Direktes Objekt)",
        "color": "purple",
        "items": [
          {
            "de": "Ich sehe den Mann.",
            "en": "I see the man. (WEN sehe ich?)"
          },
          {
            "de": "Sie kauft einen Tisch.",
            "en": "She buys a table. (WEN kauft sie?)"
          },
          {
            "de": "Wir lesen das Buch.",
            "en": "We read the book. (WAS lesen wir?)"
          },
          {
            "de": "Er hat keine Zeit.",
            "en": "He has no time."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "rules",
        "title": "Wichtige Regeln",
        "items": [
          "Nominativ: answers WER? or WAS? — always the subject.",
          "Akkusativ: answers WEN? or WAS? — the direct object.",
          "Only masculine articles change: der→den, ein→einen, kein→keinen.",
          "Feminine, neuter, and plural stay the same in Akkusativ.",
          "Many verbs require Akkusativ: haben, sehen, kaufen, lesen, finden."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "conjugation",
        "title": "Häufige Verben mit Akkusativ",
        "color": "fuchsia",
        "rows": [
          {"left": "haben", "right": "to have"},
          {"left": "brauchen", "right": "to need"},
          {"left": "sehen", "right": "to see"},
          {"left": "kaufen", "right": "to buy"},
          {"left": "lesen", "right": "to read"},
          {"left": "finden", "right": "to find"},
          {"left": "trinken", "right": "to drink"},
          {"left": "essen", "right": "to eat"},
          {"left": "kennen", "right": "to know (a person)"},
          {"left": "mögen", "right": "to like"}
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
